;; Book of Arcade Games — Chapter 15: Two Players, One Screen

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Arcade Games"
  :chapter-number      15
  :title               "Two Players, One Screen"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "arcade-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + game-design"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"Two kids, one screen. Nothing beats it. Not online multiplayer. Not
tournament play. Two humans in the same room, elbows almost touching,
watching the same screen, playing the same game with different
buttons. Sibling rivalry, best-friend teamwork, or the exquisite
tension of a couch fighting game.

Local multiplayer is the arcade's oldest form. Pong shipped as two
paddles. Chapter 15 makes any game two-player by SPLITTING THE INPUT
SPACE.

The trick: player 1 uses ('left, 'right, 'a); player 2 uses ('up,
'down, 'b). Same physics engine, same world, two entities. When the
camera has to frame both players, we introduce dynamic zoom so both
fit in view. When one player wins a round, camera-shake for both.

By chapter end you have a two-player version of any earlier chapter's
game. And you understand that the world is ONE world — two players
are just two entities the world happens to listen to.

---

## 15.1 Two paddles, one ball

The simplest possible two-player game: Pong.

```scheme
;; Two paddles, one ball. Player 1 left/right; Player 2 up/down.
(define (pong)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p1 (world/spawn 'p1 20 120))
        (p2 (world/spawn 'p2 300 120))
        (ball (world/spawn 'ball 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! p1 'rect 4 30)
    (entity/shape! p2 'rect 4 30)
    (entity/shape! ball 'circle 4)
    (entity/solid! p1 #t) (entity/solid! p2 #t) (entity/solid! ball #t)
    (entity/bounce! ball 1)   ;; perfect bounce
    (entity/set-vel! ball 3 2)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p1 0 -3))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p1 0 3))
       (when (input/down? 'up)    (entity/move! p2 0 -3))
       (when (input/down? 'down)  (entity/move! p2 0 3))
       (world/step)
       ;; Wall bounces (top/bottom).
       (let ((by (entity/y ball)) (vy (cadr (entity/vel ball))))
         (when (and (< by 5) (< vy 0))
           (entity/set-vel! ball (car (entity/vel ball)) (- vy)))
         (when (and (> by 235) (> vy 0))
           (entity/set-vel! ball (car (entity/vel ball)) (- vy))))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'p1 (entity/x p1) (entity/y p1) 4 30)
       (paint-cell 'p2 (entity/x p2) (entity/y p2) 4 30)
       (paint-cell 'ball (entity/x ball) (entity/y ball) 4 4)))))

(big-bang pong)
```

Read the input handling. Left/right control P1's Y — the paddle moves
UP and DOWN when P1 presses LEFT and RIGHT. That's arbitrary; do
whatever the players agree to. Up/down control P2.

`entity/bounce! ball 1` = perfect bounce, no energy loss. Physics
takes care of paddle reflection. Wall reflection we handle in the
`let` block after `world/step`.

The kids play. One wins a point when the ball flies past the other's
paddle. Add a scoreboard (chapter 13) and you have a full session.

---

## 15.2 Dynamic camera zoom

For a spread-across-the-screen game (racing, brawler), the camera
needs to FRAME both players. When they're close, zoom in. When they
spread apart, zoom out. Cap the zoom limits.

```scheme
;; Two players on a big map. Camera snaps to midpoint, zooms to fit.
(define (dynamic-camera)
  (world/reset!)
  (scene/grid 'ground 40 1 32 20 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 20) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  (let ((p1 (world/spawn 'p1 100 168))
        (p2 (world/spawn 'p2 200 168)))
    (entity/shape! p1 'triangle 8)
    (entity/shape! p2 'triangle 8)
    (entity/solid! p1 #t) (entity/solid! p2 #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p1 -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p1 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)  (entity/set-vel! p1 (car (entity/vel p1)) -10))
       (when (input/down? 'up)    (entity/move! p2 0 -3))
       (when (input/down? 'down)  (entity/move! p2 0 3))
       (when (input/pressed? 'b)  (entity/set-vel! p2 (car (entity/vel p2)) -10))
       ;; Camera: snap to midpoint. Zoom scales inversely with distance.
       (let* ((mx (/ (+ (entity/x p1) (entity/x p2)) 2))
              (my (/ (+ (entity/y p1) (entity/y p2)) 2))
              (d  (entity/distance p1 p2))
              (zoom (max 0.5 (min 1.5 (/ 200 (+ 100 d))))))
         (world/camera-snap! (- mx 160) (- my 120))
         ;; Zoom would go here if runtime exposes camera-zoom. If not,
         ;; keep-out bounds via camera-bounds! (dynamic).
         (world/camera-bounds! (- mx 200 (* 100 (- 1 zoom)))
                               0
                               (+ mx 200 (* 100 (- 1 zoom)))
                               240))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (world/each 'ground
                   (lambda (t) (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 20)))
       (paint-cell 'p1 (entity/x p1) (entity/y p1) 8 8)
       (paint-cell 'p2 (entity/x p2) (entity/y p2) 8 8)))))

(big-bang dynamic-camera)
```

Camera midpoint = average of the two positions. Zoom logic based on
distance. Close players see zoomed-in world; distant players see
zoomed-out.

`world/camera-snap!` positions the camera at a specific point. Not the
smooth-follow of chapter 8; two-player often benefits from immediate
snap so neither player suffers camera lag when their opponent moves.

---

## 15.3 Racing

Two ships, side-by-side.

```scheme
;; Race — two ships thrust to the right; first to x=1000 wins.
(define winner #f)

(define (race)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((s1 (world/spawn 'p1 40 100))
        (s2 (world/spawn 'p2 40 140)))
    (entity/shape! s1 'triangle 8)
    (entity/shape! s2 'triangle 8)
    (entity/drag! s1 0.02) (entity/drag! s2 0.02)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (unless winner
         (when (input/down? 'a)
           (entity/set-vel! s1 (+ 0.15 (car (entity/vel s1)))
                            (cadr (entity/vel s1))))
         (when (input/down? 'b)
           (entity/set-vel! s2 (+ 0.15 (car (entity/vel s2)))
                            (cadr (entity/vel s2))))
         ;; Vertical dodge input.
         (when (input/down? 'left)
           (entity/set-vel! s1 (car (entity/vel s1))
                            (- (cadr (entity/vel s1)) 0.5)))
         (when (input/down? 'right)
           (entity/set-vel! s1 (car (entity/vel s1))
                            (+ (cadr (entity/vel s1)) 0.5)))
         (when (input/down? 'up)
           (entity/set-vel! s2 (car (entity/vel s2))
                            (- (cadr (entity/vel s2)) 0.5)))
         (when (input/down? 'down)
           (entity/set-vel! s2 (car (entity/vel s2))
                            (+ (cadr (entity/vel s2)) 0.5)))
         (cond
           ((>= (entity/x s1) 1000) (set! winner 'p1)
                                    (world/camera-shake! 15 0.95))
           ((>= (entity/x s2) 1000) (set! winner 'p2)
                                    (world/camera-shake! 15 0.95))))
       (world/step)
       ;; Camera follows the leading player.
       (let ((leader (if (> (entity/x s1) (entity/x s2)) s1 s2)))
         (world/camera-follow! leader 0.1 60 60))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'p1 (entity/x s1) (entity/y s1) 8 8)
       (paint-cell 'p2 (entity/x s2) (entity/y s2) 8 8)
       (when winner
         (paint-text (string-append (symbol->string winner) \" WINS!\")
                     130 100))))))

(big-bang race)
```

Two ships, each with their own thruster button. Whoever hits x=1000
first wins. Camera follows the leader — the winning player sees more
of the road ahead, the losing player sees the winner's tail.

Losing feels different from winning. That difference is by DESIGN.

---

## 15.4 Cooperative

Two players share a goal — say, collectively bringing a ball to the
right side of the screen.

```scheme
;; Both players push a ball. It has to reach x=280.
(define (coop-ball)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.4)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p1 (world/spawn 'p1 40 200))
        (p2 (world/spawn 'p2 80 200))
        (ball (world/spawn 'ball 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p1 'rect 12 20) (entity/solid! p1 #t)
    (entity/shape! p2 'rect 12 20) (entity/solid! p2 #t)
    (entity/shape! ball 'circle 12) (entity/solid! ball #t)
    (entity/mass! ball 3)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p1 -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p1 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p1 (car (entity/vel p1)) -10))
       (when (input/down? 'up)    (entity/move! p2 0 -3))
       (when (input/down? 'down)  (entity/move! p2 0 3))
       (when (input/pressed? 'b)
         (entity/set-vel! p2 (car (entity/vel p2)) -10))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'p1 (entity/x p1) (entity/y p1) 12 20)
       (paint-cell 'p2 (entity/x p2) (entity/y p2) 12 20)
       (paint-cell 'ball (entity/x ball) (entity/y ball) 24 24)
       (paint-cell 'goal 280 200 20 20)
       (when (> (entity/x ball) 275)
         (paint-text \"TEAM WINS!\" 100 100))))))

(big-bang coop-ball)
```

Both players push the ball right. Neither can do it alone — the ball
is heavy (`entity/mass! ball 3`). Push together.

The kids talk more than in a competitive game. That's the coop
signature.

---

## 15.5 The four patterns

**Composition.** Each player = composition of shape + solid + tag +
input-scheme. Two players = two compositions with different input
schemes and different tags.

**Orchestration.** Frame loop orchestrates BOTH players' inputs
before physics step. Order between P1 and P2 doesn't matter (parallel
independent), but both must complete before `world/step`.

**In-routing.** Input events route per player. 'left' routes to P1's
handler; 'up' routes to P2's. That's the whole two-player trick:
routing table with different destinations for each button.

**Routing.** Both players route into the SAME physics engine. Both
players emit into the same paint pipeline. The output layer doesn't
know or care that there are two of them. The world is one world.

---

## 15.6 Common desktop tasks

**Two-operator triage.** Two operators of a shared shop can co-triage
the pending message queue: operator A takes half, operator B takes
half, they alternate for load balance. Same routing pattern, different
'players.'

**Cart-share checkout.** Two friends collaboratively fill one cart —
each of them adds items with their own cursor. Live update. Two
inputs, one shared state.

---

## 15.7 Pitfalls

**Both players push same button.** In a couch setup with two humans
and two controllers, this doesn't happen. In a keyboard setup, key
overlap can. Give players non-overlapping keys.

**Camera excludes a player.** Dynamic zoom saves it. If one player
runs offscreen, the game must decide: lock camera on them (leader-
follow), or wait for slower to catch up (rubber-band). Design choice.

**Score tied.** Design a tiebreaker or accept ties.

**Player 2 has no input at start.** Bug in the input routing table.
Test both players independently.

---

## 15.8 Try this yourself

1. Adapt any earlier chapter's game to two-player. Chapter 5 shmup:
   two ships stacked vertically. Chapter 12 boss: two players
   attacking one boss with pooled HP.
2. Player-vs-player boss: player 1 is the boss with 100 HP, player
   2 is the challenger with 5 HP. Asymmetric roles.
3. Split-screen: divide the display into two 160-wide halves,
   render P1's view left, P2's right. Requires two `world/camera`
   states — beyond this chapter, into rendering appendix territory.
4. Turn-based: only one player has input at a time; 'a' from either
   passes turn. Real chess/checkers pattern.
5. Add AI second player: 'AI thumb' presses buttons based on
   `ai/utility` scoring. Turn a two-player game into single-player
   via AI opponent.
6. Rounds: best-of-three matches. Between rounds, brief scoreboard
   screen. Chapter 14 state machine composes with this.

---

## 15.9 What we built

Pong. Dynamic camera. Racing. Coop. Four two-player shapes. Input
routing by player. Shared physics. Camera-shake for both. Whole game
family from splitting a button table.

Next chapter — the summit. You will build your own arcade game from
scratch using every technique from this book.")

